<TITLE> Delhi Metro to put Gammon India on notice </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Jul 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Gammon India will be asked to show why it should not be barred from bidding for contracts from the Delhi Metro Rail Corp (DMRC) for two years after part of a bridge it was building collapsed, a minister said on Tuesday. Jaipal Reddy, minister for urban development, told parliament that investigations had found the accident two weeks ago that killed six people was caused by design defects and improper strength of materials used. "DMRC has decided to take the following action ... the contractor Gammon India to be issued a show cause notice for blacklisting for two years," Reddy said. Shares in Gammon are down nearly 8 percent since the bridge collapsed, in contrast to the broader market that is up over 13 percent. On Tuesday, Gammon shares closed 4.5 percent higher at 148.60 rupees in a Mumbai market that was marginally 
